         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot. Garden, ¶ 9/9/66. ¶  ¶ By last mail, dear Dr Hooker, you will not have received my communications through the Colonial Office but by ordinary post, owing to the absense of Sir John Mann...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">66.09.09</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 236.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation: 'Answd Nov 19/66'. Letter not found.</p>
               </note>Melbourne bot. Garden,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">9/9/66.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By last mail, dear Dr Hooker, you will not have received my communications through the Colonial Office but by ordinary post, owing to the absense of Sir John Manners-Sutton at the time of the departure of the mail. Thus it happens that a package of seeds, which was to go to Kew last month will only be sent now. The little <name key="Cyperus">Cyperus</name> which I enclose seems a South African species<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>a South African species <seg style="font-style: italic; ">interlined above</seg> new <seg style="font-style: italic; ">deleted</seg>.</p>
               </note> and is under any circumstances an interesting addition to the N.Z. flora. Will you kindly cause the plant to be compared with existing species at Kew, and should it prove distinct cause the now transmitted diagnosis<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Neither MS or published diagnosis has been found.</p>
               </note> to be published in the L.S. proceedings or in Seemanns or the Edinburgh Journal. Should you offer any remarks, pray let them be worded so as to give me no pain. I must confess I could never write sentences such as occasionally occur in the Flora Austral, where in all eternity they will be now extant.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham had undertaken to reflect, in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora austrliensis</seg>, M's opinions where they differed from his own; see Lucas (2001). M may have been upset by comments such as '<seg style="font-style: italic; ">P</seg>[<seg style="font-style: italic; ">ultenaea</seg>] <seg style="font-style: italic; ">filifolia</seg> F Muell. Fragm. i, 9, from Kangaroo Island, Bannier, appears to me to be a luxuriant form of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">P. tenuifolia</seg> with remarkably long slender leaves, but F. Mueller's herbarium only contains a single specimen past flower, scarcely sufficient for identification' (Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2, p. 140), but there were also positive comments such as 'under the name of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">A</seg>[<seg style="font-style: italic; ">cacia</seg>] <seg style="font-style: italic; ">longifolia</seg>, I have followed F. Mueller in including the following forms, which, different as they generally appear, are connected by such a gradual chain of intermediates that they cannot be separated by any positive characters ...' (Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2, p. 398).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Pray send the fungus herewith sent to Mr Smith.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 23 October 1866, and notes thereto.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> Have you met in India or the Orient with a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">black</hi>
               </seg> fruited <name key="Melia%20Azedarach">Melia Azedarach</name>? I have the plant in Steetz's Herbarium without special indication of locality, and it would be a vast improvement to the ordinary variety which in the vernal season here looks absolutely wretched with its dirty yellow-brown drupes.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>What is <name key="Salix%20Capensis">Salix Capensis</name>?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am just publishing 2 new <name key="Aphelia">Aphelia</name>e<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3299in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3299in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B89.12.03 lists only one <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Aphelia">Aphelia</name>
                     </seg> described by M at this time: <seg style="font-style: italic; ">A. brizula</seg>, B66.12.04, p. 203. </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is no valediction; the text ends at the bottom of the sheet; part of the letter may be missing.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Aphelia">Aphelia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Cyperus">Cyperus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Melia%20Azedarach">Melia Azedarach</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Salix%20Capensis">Salix Capensis</name>
            </p>
